{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fc6503d1-b3ec-41e6-8420-f2cfe44d8a03","content":"Good questions — here's the status of those APIs:\n\n**`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — ✅ This is correct and works in .NET MAUI on .NET 10. You need the platform-specific namespace:\n\n```xml\nxmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n```\n\nThen apply it to your `ContentPage`:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage ... ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n```\n\nThis automatically adjusts the page padding to avoid the notch, Dynamic Island, and home indicator.\n\n**`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on a Grid** — ❌ This is **not** a built-in MAUI property. The tutorial is likely outdated or incorrect. There is no `IgnoreSafeArea` attached property on layout elements.\n\n### Background image behind the safe area\n\nThe common pattern is to **not** use `UseSafeArea` on the page, and instead manually pad your content:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"...\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n    <Grid>\n        <!-- Background stretches full screen, behind notch -->\n        <Image Source=\"bg.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n\n        <!-- Content respects safe area via padding -->\n        <VerticalStackLayout Padding=\"{OnPlatform iOS='20,60,20,34'}\">\n            <!-- your content here -->\n        </VerticalStackLayout>\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nFor dynamic safe area insets (varying by device), you can query them in code-behind:\n\n```csharp\nif (DeviceInfo.Platform == DevicePlatform.iOS)\n{\n    var safeInsets = On<iOS>().SafeAreaInsets();\n    MyContent.Padding = safeInsets;\n}\n```\n\nThis gives you full-bleed backgrounds while keeping content safe.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d2d7a2c3-a47f-4f17-8257-8735fdbd023b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI safe area handling on iOS, specifically about two properties:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - a platform-specific property for ContentPage\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - a property on Grid for background images\n\nLet me check the current .NET 10 documentation/status for these APIs. I know from my training data that:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was a Xamarin.Forms iOS platform-specific. In .NET MAUI, safe area handling changed. In MAUI, `Page.UseSafeArea` was initially available but the approach evolved.\n\n\n2. In .NET MAUI, the safe area handling has been reworked. The `Padding` approach with `SafeAreaInsets` or using `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` may have changed. In Xamarin.Forms, `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` was the standard approach via platform-specifics, and in .NET MAUI, this was carried forward initially but there have been changes. In .NET MAUI, `Page.UseSafeArea` is still available as an iOS platform-specific, though the exact behavior and availability of `IgnoreSafeArea` needs verification.\n\nI'm trying to pin down the current state in .NET MAUI—`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` should still be valid as a platform-specific, but I want to be careful about what's changed since the framework evolved from Xamarin.Forms. The `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` approach is definitely valid and has been available since MAUI's release, requiring the iOS platform-specific namespace. As for `IgnoreSafeArea`, I'm uncertain about its current status in .NET 10 MAUI—it may not be a standard property yet. So `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` is the correct approach for .NET MAUI and should work fine in .NET 10. If the tutorial shows `IgnoreSafeArea` as a direct property on Grid, that's likely not a standard built-in property—it might be from a custom implementation. The proper way to extend a background beyond the safe area while keeping content protected is to either skip `UseSafeArea` on the page and manually pad content elements, or use an AbsoluteLayout/Grid layering strategy instead.","outputTokens":1782,"requestId":"3C28:8F118:E0DBB2:116C548:6A012D04"},"id